gbpservice/neutron/db/migration/alembic_.message: Was there a reason you chose to do this rather than have separate provides and consumes flags? The model allows for the same contract to be both provided and consumed by an EPG.

Since the provides column is a primary key, the same contract_name can be listed for a network_id as both provides=True and provides=False. This follows the pattern used in implementing the router's existing apic:external_provided_contracts and apic:external_comsumed_contracts extension attributes. Since the provided and consumed contract extension attributes on on network (and on router) are each independent lists, the code would be a lot more complex if updating one list had to determine whether the same contract name existed on the other list, and an existing row needed to be updated rather than just added/removed.
sounds good - thanks for the explanation.

gbpservice/neutron/extensions/cisco_apic.message: I'm wondering if we can come up with a different name here? Maybe "Group"? Or just "Net"?

I get the reason for using "Extra", but somehow it didn't seem specific enough for me. I don't have a better suggestion at this point (the only ideas I had for more descriptive would make it excessively long), so I won't hold this up.

We need a name that implies that these contracts are in addition to those that are managed by attaching/removing subnets on the network to/from routers. I don't think either "group" or "net" conveys this as well as "extra", but let me know if you have a better idea

/COMMIT_MSG.message:
So Git has a feature called commit message trailers which is a series of "Key: Value" pairs attached to the footer of the commit message.

While we in JJB don't really use that feature if you want your commit message to be technically correct there should be no blank lines between "Key: Value" pairs in the footer for them to properly be picked up by Git as a commit message trailer.

jenkins_jobs/modules/triggers.py.message:
I didn't submit any tests for these error cases, I would probably need some support with that.

Nevertheless I tested it manually.
That's fine, as long as you have the XML/YAML tests.
The above mentioned properties were deprecated and are no longer supported - is it enough to log a warning when they are used or it should become a hard error?

You'd be surprised that there are possibly still orgs that have not upgraded even though it's been 5 years. I'd err on the side of caution and deprecate it with a warning message and we can remove it in a 4.x release if we ever get there.

I've uploaded patchset 2 in the meantime which doesn't take your comment into account.

However I'm afraid we cannot address all of these concerns. This change, and also one of the previous ones I made, align the XML markup with the latest version of the plugin. So it might happen that these old Jenkins installations with some old versions of the plugins will stop working when updated with XMLs from the latest JJB. I'm pretty sure that's the meaning of the new in the docs: "Jenkins Job Builder 2.x plugins are designed to default to generating the xml format for the latest supported version of JJB", right?

For example - regarding '<noNameAndEmailParameters>' - it got replaced with '<nameAndEmailParameterMode>'. Period. So some old Jenkins installations might suffer, but that's something we need to accept right?

"Deprecated" and "no longer supported" are 2 entirely different concepts. When you deprecate something you are logging a warning that support will be removed in a future release but users can continue to use this feature for the time being. So I would argue that you are not "deprecating" a feature if you are removing it's support entirely.

Typically we follow semvar in JJB so we would deprecate in the current version, and remove support when/if we release 4.x version later in the future. Do not assume people are upgrading to the latest version of software because there are many organizations that are slow at getting the latest releases out. For example OpenDev is still on Gerrit 2.13.

For features that have changed their input keys can we support the old format as a fallback (set the default to get value from the old configuration while new configuration overrides)?

Then just leave a warning so that folks have time to migrate their configuration until we release a major version that breaks backwards compatibility like 4.x.

You're totally right. I went too far with these changes, for the benefit of simplified implementation and maintenance.

The idea with defaults from the old input keys and overriding with the new ones is fine for me. I will update the code accordingly.

One more question regarding "trigger-for-unreviewed-patches" - is it OK to completely drop support for it as it's no longer supported by the plugin since v2.14.0, so for almost 5 years now?

  upgrade:

releasenotes/notes/custom-certificates-5.message:
This part isn't really clear. If you run ``kolla-ansible certificates`` without custom config, it will try to generate them into ``$KOLLA_CONFIG_PATH/certificates`` rather than ``$KAYOBE_CONFIG_PATH/kolla/certificates``.

In my experience this fails unless ``kolla_external_fqdn_cacert`` is also set.
I was thinking exactly about instructions for generating certificates in the right place through Kayobe. This will do for now and we can improve in another patch.

It's necessary but not sufficient :) I got it working by running 'kolla-ansible certificates -e kolla_certificates_dir=$KAYOBE_CONFIG_PATH/kolla/certificates', and setting kolla_external_fqdn_cacert. It would be nice if it was a bit smoother, and it needs documenting.

What do you think we should say here?
